        <h1>1.4 de Broglie Waves</h1>
        <p>A de Broglie wave represents the probability of finding a particle. Unlike a classical string wave, this is a wave of "probability amplitude."</p>

        <div class="equation-box">
            $$\Psi(x,t) = A e^{i(kx - \omega t)}$$
        </div>

        <p>Here, $k = 2\pi/\lambda$ is the wave vector and $\omega$ is the angular frequency. These waves are essential in describing particles at the atomic scale.</p>

