    <div class="a4-page" id="page5">
        <h1>1.5 Group and Phase Velocity</h1>
        <p>A single wave velocity (phase velocity $v_p$) cannot represent a particle. Instead, we use a "wave packet" which travels at the group velocity ($v_g$).</p>

        <div class="equation-box">
            $$v_p = \frac{\omega}{k}, \quad v_g = \frac{d\omega}{dk}$$
        </div>

        <p>For a non-relativistic particle, it can be shown that the group velocity $v_g$ is exactly equal to the classical particle velocity $v$.</p>
        
